# ================================================================
DEVIN ACU OPTIMIZATION GUIDE — DOS AND DON’TS

## 1 ACU ≈ 15 minutes of active work | $2.25/ACU (Core) | $2.00/ACU (Team)

# ================================================================
✅ THE DOS — MAXIMIZE EVERY ACU

## DO 1 — PROVIDE A “GOLDEN REFERENCE” FILE

Instead of describing a pattern, point Devin to an existing file
that already demonstrates it. Devin won’t waste ACUs scanning
the entire codebase to guess your style.

✗ COSTLY:
“Create a new UserReport service following our project
conventions.”
→ Devin scans the whole repo to infer conventions.

✓ EFFICIENT:
“Create a new UserReport service. Use AccountReport.java
as the exact template — same structure, error handling,
and logging pattern.”
→ Devin goes straight to the reference. No scan needed.

## DO 2 — USE “ASK DEVIN” (CHAT MODE) TO SCOPE BEFORE CODING

Chat mode uses fewer resources than a full coding session.
Gather facts first, then give a precise instruction.

✗ COSTLY:
[Coding session]
“Find where DB migrations live and figure out the naming
convention, then create one for the new payments table.”
→ Discovery + execution mixed = expensive.

✓ EFFICIENT:
[Ask Devin first — chat mode]
“Where are DB migrations stored and what’s the naming
convention?”

```
[Then coding session]
"Create migration in /db/migrations/ named
 V23__add_payments_table.sql with columns: id, amount,
 status, created_at."
→ Discovery is cheap; execution is precise.
```

## DO 3 — SUPPLY EXPLICIT, MACHINE-VERIFIABLE ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA

Without a clear “done” signal, Devin loops — guesses it’s
finished, finds a crack, retries. A specific test command
short-circuits this loop entirely.

✗ COSTLY:
“Fix the login bug and make sure it works.”
→ Open-ended. Devin self-critiques and retries indefinitely.

✓ EFFICIENT:
“Fix the null pointer in AuthService.java line 42.
Run: mvn test -Dtest=UserAuthTest
Only open a PR if all 3 tests pass.
Stop and report if they don’t.”
→ Binary done/fail signal. No loop.

## DO 4 — BREAK LARGE TASKS INTO VERTICAL SLICES

Complexity cost is exponential. A 5-hour task that fails wastes
all 5 hours. Five 1-hour slices give you 4 wins even if one
fails. There’s no concurrent session limit — parallelise.

✗ COSTLY:
“Upgrade the whole project to Spring Boot 3, fix all
breaking changes, update all tests, and update the
deployment config.”
→ Monolithic. One failure loses everything.

✓ EFFICIENT:
Session A: “Update pom.xml deps only. Run compile,
report errors.”
Session B: “Fix compile errors in /security module only.”
Session C: “Fix compile errors in /api module only.”
Session D: “Update test configs after B+C are merged.”
→ Isolated, recoverable, parallelisable.

## DO 5 — REVIEW AND TRIM THE PLAN BEFORE DEVIN STARTS CODING

Interactive Planning is essentially free. Letting Devin execute
a bloated plan costs real ACUs. A 2-minute plan review can
eliminate hours of misdirected work.

✗ COSTLY:
Devin’s plan: “Search entire /src directory for
relevant files…”
[You click Approve without reading]
→ You pay for a broad scan you didn’t need.

✓ EFFICIENT:
Devin’s plan: “Search entire /src directory…”
[You edit before approving]:
“The logic you need is only in /src/services/auth —
search there only. Skip /src/legacy entirely.”
→ Scope cut before a single ACU is spent on execution.

## DO 6 — PRE-LOAD CONTEXT INTO THE KNOWLEDGE BASE

Every session where Devin re-discovers your API conventions,
coding standards, or infra setup is wasted ACUs. Store once;
Devin reads them instantly every session.

✗ COSTLY:
“Research which logging library we use and how we
structure API responses, then implement the endpoint.”
→ Rediscovery cost paid every single session.

✓ EFFICIENT:
[Knowledge base has: api-standards.md, logging-guide.md]
“Implement the /orders endpoint. Follow the API standards
and logging guide already in your Knowledge base.”
→ Zero discovery cost. Instant context.

# ================================================================
❌ THE DON’TS — ACU TRAPS TO AVOID

## DON’T 1 — AVOID SUBJECTIVE OR QUALITATIVE INSTRUCTIONS

Words like “cleaner,” “better,” or “more modern” have no exit
condition. Devin attempts multiple approaches, self-critiques,
and iterates — an expensive loop with no guaranteed end.

✗ ACU TRAP:
“Refactor this code to be cleaner and more modern.”
“Make the UI look better.”
“Improve overall performance.”
→ No measurable done state. Runs until ACUs run out.

✓ PRECISE ALTERNATIVE:
“Refactor PaymentService.java: extract the 3 private
methods into a new PaymentValidator class. No logic
changes — just structural reorganisation.”
“Change primary button color to #3B82F6, font-size to 16px.”
“Add index on orders.customer_id. Target: query under 200ms.”

## DON’T 2 — DON’T MIX RESEARCH + IMPLEMENTATION IN CODING MODE

Browser-based research in a coding session is expensive — Devin
opens tabs, reads docs, compares options. Do research in chat
mode or externally; then give Devin just the decision.

✗ ACU TRAP:
[Coding session]
“Research which caching library is best for our Spring
Boot app, decide, then implement it.”
→ High browser usage + thinking time in expensive mode.

✓ PRECISE ALTERNATIVE:
[You decide externally: use Caffeine cache]
[Coding session]
“Add Caffeine cache to ProductService.java.
Cache getProductById() with TTL=10min, max 500 entries.
Reference: https://github.com/ben-manes/caffeine”
→ Decision made before the session starts.

## DON’T 3 — DON’T ENABLE AUTO-RELOAD FOR NEW/COMPLEX PROMPTS

If Devin enters a loop (implement → test fails → fix → same
failure → fix differently → repeat), auto-reload silently
refills the ACU tank and the loop continues overnight.

✗ ACU TRAP:
Auto-reload = ON
New complex task: “Migrate entire DB schema to new ORM”
[Devin loops on a migration error × 40 retries]
→ Wake up to $90 in ACU charges.

✓ SAFER APPROACH:
Auto-reload = OFF for new/complex tasks.
Run 1 session. Review Session Insights.
If it succeeds → consider enabling auto-reload for this
type of task going forward.
If it loops → fix the prompt first, then retry.

## DON’T 4 — DON’T BUNDLE MULTI-TOPIC TASKS IN ONE SESSION

Every context switch forces Devin to load a new mental model
of a different codebase area. Each switch adds overhead. If
one part fails, the entire session cost is wasted.

✗ ACU TRAP:
“Fix the login bug, then update the README, then refactor
the payment module, then add tests for the cart service.”
→ 4 context switches. One failure = full session wasted.

✓ PRECISE ALTERNATIVE:
Session A: “Fix login bug in AuthService.java line 42.”
Session B: “Update README deployment section with these
new steps: [steps here].”
Session C: “Refactor PaymentModule to use
IPaymentGateway interface.”
Session D: “Add unit tests for CartService covering:
addItem, removeItem, calcTotal.”
→ Isolated, parallelisable, each independently reviewable.

## DON’T 5 — DON’T SEND DEVIN INTO A LARGE CODEBASE UNSCOPPED

A monorepo with 200k lines costs significantly more per action
than pointing Devin at 3 specific files. More context to
process = higher ACU cost per step.

✗ ACU TRAP:
“Find where order status update logic is and fix the bug
where cancelled orders aren’t being notified.”
→ Full repo search. Expensive.

✓ PRECISE ALTERNATIVE:
“Fix bug in OrderService.java → updateStatus() method.
When status = CANCELLED, the notifyCustomer() call on
line 87 is skipped. It should always fire.
Only touch this file.”
→ 1 file, 1 method, 1 fix. Minimal context load.

